@realDonaldTrump At first blush, Barr’s statement seems to be a step in the right direction for an Attorney General turned the DOJ into in-house counsel for The Trump Organization. On reflection, Barr’s statement is about Barr feeling sorry for himself. He talks about “me” and

“my job.” Notice who Barr doesn’t mention? The four prosecutors that Trump attacked as “rogue prosecutors” who “should go back to school.” Barr also offered a lame defense for his disgraceful reversal of the sentencing recommendation for Roger Stone.

@realdonaldtump It is difficult to understate how radical Barr’s intervention in the Stone sentencing was. Federal law provides guidelines to ensure uniformity and fairness in sentences for similarly-situated defendants. Prosecutors are required to submit sentencing memoranda

that explain how their recommendations align with the sentencing guidelines. The original sentencing memorandum was a thoughtful, 24-page analysis of the guidelines and recommended 7 to 9 nine years in prison. The revised 5‑ page memo acknowledges that the guidelines call for 7

to 9 years in prison, but asked the judge to ignore the fact that Stone threatened a witness to “prepare to die” and says that threatening the witness was just part of the overall obstruction of justice of lying to Congress. The revised memorandum also says that the judge

should consider the “advanced age and health” of Roger Stone—who is a well-known weight-lifter and body-builder. At root, the revised memo submitted by Bill Barr asks the judge to ignore the federal sentencing guidelines because . . . well, because Trump said so in a tweet.

Nobody should feel sorry for Bill Barr. The only reason that Trump’s tweets are making it hard for Barr to do “his” job is because Trump is being transparent about what Barr’s “job” is—protecting Trump.

@realdonaldtump Over the last two days, Trump attacked everyone involved in the Roger Stone case—except Roger Stone, who was convicted of lying to Congress to protect Trump. Trump attacked the following: The prosecutors who resigned from the Stone case when Bill Barr

intervened, saying that “they should go back to school” and were “rogue prosecutors.” The forewoman of the jury convicted Roger Stone, saying she had “significant bias.” The judge who will decide Stone’s prison sentence, falsely claiming that she placed Paul Manafort

in solitary confinement. In short, Trump attacked the entire system of justice in the US. Every American who values the rule of law should be outraged. Trump is bludgeoning the justice system to bend to his will. Democrats called on the Chief Justice of the United States,

John Roberts, to defend the judiciary. See The Guardian, “Roger Stone case: chief justice urged to step in as Trump's 'abuse of power' condemned.” As Roberts did in Trump’s impeachment trial, he has remained silent. But if Trump resorts to pettifogging, we should expect
Chief Justice Roberts to leap into action!
